			<font face=helvetica size=-1>
<font face=helvetica size=3><b>Saturday September 30, 2000</b></font>
			<hr align=LEFT size=1 width=500 color=#000080>
<!---------------news---------------->
<Br>
<font face=helvetica size=2 color=#000080><b>Why Editing is Important To All Of Us</b> - 15:03:46</font>
<br><br><blockquote>
The <a href=http://www.err-network.com/article_weii.shtml>ERR Network</a> has posted an article explaining why people feel the urge to edit and create new content for the 3D games they play.  Here's a clip:
<blockquote>
But what drives people to edit? What makes people like you and me tick to build maps, levels, mods, logo's, models and so on? One simple reason is that we love a game. Everyone who likes a game and eventually gets bored playing it (or doesn't), wants to do more with it. Some open a fansite, start a clan or tribe and others start mapping, modeling, skinning, painting and so on. It's this erge to continue on the game though you already finished it (or didn't). The game attracts you, you want to recreate it, continue it, make it larger, put in your own creativity or you just love it to see something in a game that YOU made yourself. It's all psychological.
</blockquote>
Check out the full story <a href=http://www.err-network.com/article_weii.shtml>here</a>.
<b><p align=right>Update by <a href="mailto:hypnos@qeradiant.com">Hypno|S|</a></p></b>
</blockquote>
<h3>Go <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net">back</a> to the main news page...</h3>
			</font>
